  "prompt": "Why AC produces water?",
  "response": "Air conditioners produce water because of a process called **condensation**. Here's a breakdown of the science behind it:\n\n*   **Warm Air Holds Moisture:** Warm air can hold more water vapor than cold air. This is why it feels more humid in the summer.\n*   **Cooling and Dehumidification:** Air conditioners work by circulating refrigerant through coils. The indoor coil becomes very cold. As warm, humid air from your room passes over this cold coil, the air cools down significantly.\n*   **Reaching the Dew Point:** As the air cools, it reaches its \"dew point.\" The dew point is the temperature at which the air becomes saturated with water vapor. When the air cools below the dew point, it can no longer hold all the moisture.\n*   **Condensation Occurs:** The excess water vapor in the air condenses into liquid water on the cold coil. Think of it like a cold glass of water on a humid day \u2013 water droplets form on the outside of the glass.\n*   **Drainage:** The water that condenses on the coil drips into a drain pan and is then usually routed outside through a drain line.\n\nIn simpler terms: The AC cools the air, and cool air can't hold as much moisture, so the moisture turns into water.\n\nIf your AC isn't draining water properly, or producing far more water than usual, it may have a problem that needs to be addressed.\n",
